How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases only trips to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after which the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechs) were not allowed to travel freely and individually not even by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend all night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, it wasn't all won.
The so-called "change promise" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable person," who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way the Czechs travel has been undergoing a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was not for us to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria anymore, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the current favourite destination, Croatia, until 1989, could not be travelled freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
In the early 1990s, the visa exemption was imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European States, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechs, for a long time, did not see themselves sick of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the Czech groups slept in the parks in the country stores, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take with it the food (conservations, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech krona, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it the average wages, which about 1997 resulted in an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand the agencies began, from 1997 onwards regularly, to prepare the trips using charter flights connections, which caused the travel prices to drop dramatically compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90th century, the Czechs were already travelling visaless to almost all developed countries except the United States, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists leave each year, making countries far and hot. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, so our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head on foreign travel, including expenses on the site of stay.
