But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in an interview to newly rediscovered Jobs that has been dismantled as the advance of a series of special projections in the larger markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of the products.
It was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer, and hippie, but it was also a meticulous organizer and an enuki of flow diagrams - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the TV series The Triumph of the Nerds on the top of the personal computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time they had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and already worked intensively in their new NeXT computer company, waiting for popular Internet adoption.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said that the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs died that a complete copy of VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This archive material, slightly reissued, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and commercial strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where it seems impatient due to Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster towards the subjects or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies see doing right and wrong, and offers their own vision of the future of computer science.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Job's career, but there's something raw and inspiring in the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how they can and must be things.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked: "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you in an invariable way are: "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
