And again, no one who lives will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about the traps in school and university exams are very widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given the exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and deception are acceptable.
How much deceit do we have?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for personal as well as professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted deep research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been rebutted.
Liars do look in the eyes.
They don't always stutter, gossip, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years testing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and help to navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from research that the extroverts lie more than the introverts, that men say more "lies oriented towards themselves", while women say more lies "orientated towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their mates than those who are not married (but the lies they say tend to be "great").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty when lying to you.
How to know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual conduct of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the posture of the subject, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's better to know if someone usually beats his foot all the time not to make unfair accusations when he sees his feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and nonverbal behavioural groups.
Consider these behavioural groups as warning signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change their position significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview eviction" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
The interviewers often falsely see that the interview has ended only in search of that post-interview relief.
It also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson stepped to the bottom and used the time ago as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distant language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I understand myself."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
