Climate adversity halted the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and contracted the economy
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-denominated of change, which generated great expectations for progress in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses to the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction in economic activity in general of 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of impacts on the icelands, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was sustained in 582 thousand 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main sinister crops were those of vegetables, corn and garb.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of State unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was seen as an accelerated growth, since by January to March 55 thousand,053 signposters were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate rose to 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in number of persons dropped to more than 74,000 unemployed signposters, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have taken since public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth in unemployment which has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a restriction of resources by the legislation passed at the Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who seize dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Organisation
López Cervantes pointed out that there is also a demographic factor in increasing unemployment.
"The number of people leaving the state looking for work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties of entering, and secondly because entering already have many difficulties to find work, these people are staying and demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the signal labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality prevailing among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in the state works without being listed as a worker before any social security institution.
Together with unemployment and informality, another of the state's job losses is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Insurance Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of signal workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Together with the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011, the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment over the past 10 years is recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June of the State FDI amounted to $630,697, representing a decrease of 87,74 per cent compared to the $5,143,312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos per year, mainly from third-party companies.
Debt
In the light of the economic contraction scenario, the State Government requested in July the state congress to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, even though investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities would be aimed at re-activated the economy, the approval of the local congress was of an amount of 2 billion pesos, and until November they did not observe the benefits of debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For business sector representatives, Mario López Valdés' first year of government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has really been very poor, we must work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, we have failed to align the effort of everyone and above all the good march already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López reported that events such as early-year ice cream stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including ice cream, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that doesn't turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year, we are closing far below the expectations we had," he mentioned.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the National Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he stated that it is necessary to bring the state into productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is depleted," he said.
Work to be done
The Chairman of the Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a vision for the future that better governs the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has been working hard to achieve good results in different areas of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He pointed out that the current administration has shown progress in its conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that allow me to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
