In his speech, the President-in-Office said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive could not structure through general rules the measures for the preparation of public administration.
"I also do not consider that if I did so, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the Federal Executive, who has the constitutional mandate, the state's rectory.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, and it translates into better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he said, would delay the benefits of digitisation, which involves a decision of public interest, which has not only a technical dimension, "for it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
