The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Pre-Trial Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total records.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), Maria de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on 9 November, the electoral body adopted a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Act, provided that the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period so that they could enter into force in this electoral process and Governor Leone Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits set out in the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local Legislative Power and called as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the State representative on constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", Maria de los Angeles Llanderal explained that through the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the EMI it will be possible to conduct partial and total polling accounts by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be made on the assumption that: the results of the records do not coincide; there is no ballot and calculation in the case of the box or does not operate by the chairman of the register; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations of the records.
In addition, the total number of votes received in all the ballot boxes may be made when there is evidence that the difference between the alleged candidate winner of the election concerned and the one who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is the express request of the party representative and/or coalition that applied for the second of the nominated candidates.
The total vote may also be counted if at the end of the ordinary calculation it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the second candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate remained second, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of partial counting will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation there is the choice of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total records.
