Italian Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of the economic disaster and has put the whole eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take over.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The frame is now well outlined," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, while Italy fights a political and financial crisis that has driven the costs of its debt at unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain the strong confidence in Italy.
Stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the performance of the Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were obliged to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly driven by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis forced him to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are meant to have a good outcome," he told the press Angelino Alfano, secretary of the mid-right party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocratic majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Government of Monti must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks came under pressure to warn that a failure in Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
It will end its round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels among uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister will succeed.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
Monti has said that his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections are made.
Monti has said that he would like to include politicians in his office, but the big parties insist that it should be formed only by technicians, an indication of his repairs to a process bound by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual mistrust and disagreement between parties are making it difficult to include political figures.
