MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Insurance Conducts an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducts a research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetic protocol of obesity in children and adolescents', which will allow them to have markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialties Hospital of the National Medical Center 21th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionologists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population to participate whether or not they are eligible, to visit the IMSS sports units participating in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Quauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of West Mexico) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of East Mexico).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is fulfilled, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Sports Morelos Unit (northern of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
At the celebration of the World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he stated that the aim was to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of disease, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, blood glucose level determination, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (we seek to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concerns of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years, there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 per cent in obesity, and of girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight a dramatic rise was also observed', said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population differs from others by their genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of Indian American heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that overall, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, allowing to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even he said, the presence of dark-coloured folds (canthosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even predisabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they must make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport rather than walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the increased consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid baccalaureates
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sending the floor were taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand baths each season of rain in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that if the process of building and maintaining an asphalt floor is adequate, the baths could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the baccles, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of baches.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules, called asphaltenes, and other low molecular weights, called Maltese, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists of that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves as a liquid, 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and 50 degrees centigrade has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform, but that it is changing during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphaltic folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pieritas that constitute the folder, pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, placed a last layer called a bearing folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
Since it is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the bearing folder also requires the appropriate thickness and the material to be taken care of is to be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is moistened, the water spreads inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a re-balancing of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of baches.
In the process of forming a boat, he said, the first to wear is the rolling film and only afterwards is affected by the asphalt folder, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of baccalaureates and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the floor should always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, in order to avoid frequent baccalation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to be done to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair the bags easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
