So was the work of the master who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A clofoscopeist from Cali passed to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these staff members is key.
On November 4th, a clofoscopeist from Cali's ITC passed to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the FARC's top leader: "Alfonso Cano", through the cottage of his fingerprints.
Of the seven Lophoscopists working in the ITC section, that week he played the "availability" shift to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has worked in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
When he began his career, González worked in municipalities of the Chocó, where he often had to stay in the jungle for more than five days to reach the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, specialized in loposcopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms of hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar warned him to wear minimum clothing for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca on a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew he should identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being one of the men who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry Guillermo León Sáenz's decacticular card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, since it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was without a beard, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian lens, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man coming from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming to the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the chief of the Farcs.
In search of the fingerprint
For a fingerprinter of the Sijín de Cali the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without any margin of error, which can become key to solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, Lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals have false IDs or no papers.
We take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The investigator told him that, in a case of theft, he was moved to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a strong box full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces for fingerprinting, but in that case we could get the mark from all hands and identify the offender, who had participated in various thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
They recently found a dead man with bottles of liquor around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a mark on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprinter explained that in the objects "the prints are extracted with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is played becomes footprint.
However, if it can be used, if it is performed the respective cottage.
The "indignified" challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators flocked in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part answered the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to enter again, under a court order, at Manhattan Square from which they were left early in the morning and trying to occupy another Grand Manzana Park.
Hundreds of demonstrators flocked to Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access to a court order that allowed the "indignants" to re-camp in the place, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to re-camp in the square, we will settle somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sittings and demonstrations," said one of the spokespersons of the "Occupa Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the "indignant" to the eviction of his camp, personally dictated by New York mayor Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting forced evacuation of the place and allowed demonstrators to remain camped.
In addition, the "indignant" proceeded to occupy a new park located in the confluence of Canal Street and the Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, and property of the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray was unable to confirm the concrete figure, while he assured Ephège that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization assures that several hundred people had been installed at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders had already been displaced in support of the members of the movement and had tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a private-owned building - remains closed pending a judicial hearing scheduled for this same Tuesday in which the legality of the evacuation of this morning should be analysed.
Some of the demonstrators so far carried and distributed copies of that court order to these hours and even handed them over to the agents who were guarding the square, which led to "some small clashes," said Bray, who reported that some officers had proposed strikes to the protesters.
The court order prohibits the authorities from dislodging the members of Occupa Wall Street or applying "laws that were issued after the occupation began or prohibit demonstrators from accessing the park again with shops or other properties they used previously."
Mayor Bloomberg pointed out to the press that, because of this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and the demonstrators, to whom he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to re-install themselves with tents and sleeping bags.
The registrar personally defended the eviction of Zuccotti Square early in the morning, an operation in which about 200 arrests were carried out and which was decided because the protesters were "violeting the law".
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "in a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to harm other people", because "some businesses had received threats" and the neighbors feared "because of their quality of life".
"The eviction of this morning was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of "missing respect for freedom of expression."
The "Occupa Wall Street" officials also indicated that they intend to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community and trade unions, to commemorate the two months that the protests lasted, which began on 17 September.
