Japan reindeer after the earthquake
GDP grows 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of falls that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescent by the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster Japan has suffered since World War II.
The Government of Tokyo ' s first estimates amounted to $300 billion in material losses, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to move on, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at an annual rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth from January to March 2010.
Recovery is partly explained by the resurgence of the purchase of machinery to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1 per cent, compared to the decline of 0.9% in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first downturn after six months of uninterrupted climbs.
However, the true repulsiveness of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use the shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable rose by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the internal market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refuge values" chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro area and the troubled US forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a coward in the accounts of the exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious reversal for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of the major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, found their weak results between July and September to the Yen's contribution.
While the markets continue to be besieged by the peripheral countries of the EU, the Yoshihiko Noda Government does not pay attention.
"There is a need to pay attention to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand's floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday, Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And, indeed, prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) specified that the majority of member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates inflection points in the world economy highlighted that the major powers are slowing down.
Since it dropped four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 August.
The euro area was even below the average, which is at level 100, by falling eight tenths to 99.13 points.
Athens once again feeds on doubts
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the conservatives will not sign any written compromise
With the peripheral risk premiums fired and the uncertainty resettled in the parks, Greece continues to be entangled in the maze leading to the outbreak of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek Transitional Government is more imposed by the requirements of Brussels than by genuine political conviction begins to be confirmed by facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there was no alternative for structural reforms and that the hundred-day period agreed in his appointment might be short to implement them, conservative party leader New Democracy Antonis Samaras assured that he would not support new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections for the scheduled date on 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the summit of 26 October," Papadimos said yesterday, opening a parliamentary debate that will conclude tomorrow with a vote of confidence to the new Executive.
A package with 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the disciplinary code of officials and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not express any doubt about his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the transitional government, but we have not committed ourselves to anything else."
The conservative leader was a step further in his pulse to the EU and the IMF, the agencies that must unlock the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and made it clear that he will not give his visa to any letter of commitment to comply with the adjustments.
But the European Commission, which is still aware of the impact caused by the Papandreu referendum order, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock the aid if the new Government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity and as soon as possible".
The spokesperson for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the Troika inspectors will return "very soon" to Athens to discuss with the new government "what is needed to pay the sixth instalment" of 8 billion, although there is no definitive date.
The Greek wood still has thread for a while.
Madame Sofia: "These are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen highlights Spain's "preponderant" place in relation to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a dominant place at the global level in the role of Microfinance".
Queen Doña Sofia recalled yesterday that the country has become in these last two decades the second donor of the proposal in relation to this instrument of cooperation, whose "essence" stated that it is a "tool for social progress, justice and hope for a better future for all humanity, based on trust in human beings".
The Queen opened yesterday the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the conviction that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Goals established by the United Nations by 2015 horizon, and, "very especially, in that it aims at halving the volume of people living with incomes less than one dollar a day, with which the "poor threshold" is set."
Spain "keeps working" to expand the network of beneficiaries "to every corner of the planet, and takes on this task with "responsibility," said Doña Sofia, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions that originate at the Summit, which will extend until Thursday, "will guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest, and especially for women", the main beneficiaries of these loans.
They are "many of the achievements achieved" and "many of the challenges we face."
The Microcredit Summit presents itself not only as a forum for discussion, but also as the platform from which to promote "two basic goals".
Thus, His Majesty explained that it is expected that by the end of 2015 there will be 175 million poor families that have accessed these financial services and that hundreds of millions of these households will emerge from the poverty line in which they are submerged.
The momentum in the conception of microcredit in Spain and the rest of the world "has followed the path begun years ago in a pioneer way" by Muhammad Yunus, highlighted Doña Sofia as an "act of justice and due recognition".
