An expert committee states that euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized
Canadians live by denying death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls for Governments, health-care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not only in cases of cancer.
Canadian society lives by denying death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements for that purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, which included the participation of six experts from various areas, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient raises this option and has been judged competent to take the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada occupies tenth place, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that are inconsistent with the Federal Government's position, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, which have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not resulted in an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, claimed yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians, in favour of euthanasia
