Energy policy:
facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an election meeting should be time to reflect on these issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will mean doubling electricity demand by 2050, unless a large part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing shortage of fossil resources must be alleviated in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
That is not the case either of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or Switzerland, which aims only to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, for example, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, returning to the construction of a disrupted power plant following the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such speech.
The election of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
Within a few months, the harmful effects will be noted.
Consideration should be given to the case of Denmark.
Europe's champion in the wind sector, of which 30% of its electricity is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to wind intermittent; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill of 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would leave realism to the wonderful declarations about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price which the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not manifest opposition to that kind of energy by principle, according to surveys.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 executive jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Extensively export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and which can create non-relocable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would entail the sacrifice of much of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion annually in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would charge an EPR designed to work sixty years, when it is expected to collapse its manufacturer?
In order to solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no devilish source.
The development by Areva of low-carbon and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of security.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamenville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause any consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of an unprecedented magnitude, which led to the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
