The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from a number of points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the figure policy, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights countries" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students who have jumped the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely considered economically.
The question is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem for a country with about two million migrant workers", while on the left, the tone was Michel Rocard saying that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are regarded as a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande limited himself to including trivialities, indicating that the coderroll will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly those who are less qualified, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that immigrants are actually rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly employed in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national and most skilled workers in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there was a lack of anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants led to a positive impact on the wages and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows represents an increase in real long-term wages from 0.6 to 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there are a large proportion of American Nobel prizes naturalized and businesses such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches 30 years of age will make a net contribution (less-expenditure income) of EUR 150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term of office, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to look for the missing growth points "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
