The North Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which communicates directly with Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a big pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic shores, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, the Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 million cubic metres of extra Russian gas will arrive every year to Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km communicating the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, that is enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, it is already discussed the possibility of building a third tube through the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land use by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening it to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But price is a weakening of the Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to succeed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and wealthy Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that joins us organically," said François Fillon during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the great contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the managers of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from the anchorages of ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, by precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream society.
It was also necessary to extort measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but the project managers gave up on it, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to establish itself permanently on the sea opposite their shores.
"In case of damage, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
However, the manufacturers consider an escape unlikely, since they have planned joints that they will have a flight every 100,000 years, according to the forecasts.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, which conducts external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the form of a pure, it is inserted inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full journey days at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the stakes.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favourable.
After that, Gazprom rented the company, for a period of 25 years renewable, the entire gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay you for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually being transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been brought to an end by 30 per cent with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70 per cent through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.400 million for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom assumes the risk of expenditure alone.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Some valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its rectangular black pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the present appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a book of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, took care of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the soft skin skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, up to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years has been far away, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, as the notebook attracts businessmen as well as students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginning, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in downtown cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise in emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with Moleskine's development: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard caps, at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer wallpapers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the whole population.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress achieved for 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there's still a lot to be done."
It should be mentioned that disabled persons continue to face many obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (an average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not completed the bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the main problem," says Christian Grapin, general director of Tremtlin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur Association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge on low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of persons in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far away from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Ageffiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishment "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law that increased contributions has generated great pressure for businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a genuine awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
